-- Stocks in South Africa Climb, Led By Absa, Billiton, Sasol, Standard Bank
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-06-14T13:43:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/south-african-stocks-rise-led-by-absa-bhp-billiton-sasol-standard-bank.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  gained 451.04, or 1.7 percent, to 27,300.21 by 3:42
p.m. in Johannesburg. A close at this level would be the highest
this month.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Absa Group Ltd.  (ASA SJ), South Africa’s largest retail
bank, gained for the first time in three days, advancing 2.73
rand, or 2.2 percent, to 125.78 rand. Deutsche Bank AG equity
analyst Voyt Krzychylkiewicz raised his recommendation on the
stock to “buy” from “sell” with a 12-month price estimate of
145 rand.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, climbed 6.62 rand, or 3.2 percent, to 216.69 rand,
bringing its gain in the past week to 11 percent.  Anglo American
Plc  (AGL SJ) increased 9.60 rand, or 3.3 percent, to 297.29
rand. Copper rose for a fifth day, and was on pace for its
longest rally in more than five months, on signs of sustained
demand in China after domestic inventories fell for a sixth
week. Nickel, zinc and lead advanced.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, increased 7.79 rand, or 2.8 percent, to 282.04
rand. A close at this price would be the biggest rally since
Feb. 16. Crude oil climbed in New York to trade at more than $75
a barrel on speculation that the economy of the U.S., the
world’s biggest energy consumer, will boost fuel demand.  
 Standard Bank Group Ltd.  (SBK SJ), Africa’s largest lender,
climbed 2.08 rand, or 2 percent, to 105.08 rand, its biggest
intraday gain in more than a week. Deutsche Bank analyst
Krzychylkiewicz raised his recommendation on the stock to
“buy” from “hold” with a 12-month price estimate of 120 rand
a share.  
